### MVC Architecture

The **Cab Booking Application** is built using the **Model-View-Controller (MVC)** architectural pattern, which separates the application into three distinct layers: **Model**, **View (Routes)**, and **Controller**. This structure improves code organization, maintainability, scalability, and makes collaborative development easier.

#### Model Layer (Data Layer)

The **Model** layer manages all data-related operations. It defines the structure of the application's data using **Mongoose schemas** and handles interactions with the **MongoDB** database. This layer is responsible for creating, reading, updating, and deleting (CRUD) data while ensuring consistency and validation.

**Responsibilities:**

* Define database schemas using Mongoose
* Perform CRUD operations on MongoDB
* Validate and manage application data
* Maintain data integrity

---

#### Controller Layer (Business Logic Layer)

The **Controller** layer serves as the bridge between the routes and the models. It receives incoming HTTP requests, processes user input, performs validations when required, communicates with the appropriate model, and sends the response back to the client.

**Responsibilities:**

* Handle incoming API requests
* Process business logic
* Validate request data
* Interact with models
* Return appropriate HTTP responses

---

#### View Layer (Routing Layer)

Since this project is a **RESTful backend API**, the **View** is represented by the **Routing Layer**. Routes define the available API endpoints and map HTTP methods such as **GET**, **POST**, **PUT**, and **DELETE** to their respective controller functions.

**Responsibilities:**

* Define API endpoints
* Route client requests to controllers
* Organize application endpoints
* Handle RESTful API communication

---

### MVC Workflow

```text
Client Request
       │
       ▼
Routes (View Layer)
       │
       ▼
Controllers (Business Logic)
       │
       ▼
Models (Mongoose)
       │
       ▼
MongoDB Database
       │
       ▼
Controller
       │
       ▼
Response to Client
```

